To solve this, we can use dynamic programming. Let dp[i][j] represent the minimum number of operations needed to modify the first i integers in nums such that the subarray [i, j] has all elements greater than or equal to k.

We can initialize dp[0][i] to be the number of operations needed to modify the first i integers in nums such that the subarray [i, i] has the maximum element greater than or equal to k. We can then use the recurrence relation dp[i][j] = min(dp[i - 1][j - 1] + 1, dp[i][j - 1] + 1) to fill in the rest of the dp table.

Finally, we can return the minimum value of dp[i][j] for all i, j.
